<br>
To those who wonder why other classes worry about a druid petition, and those that feel that only druids know enough to respond, and those that feel that suggestions should only apply to druids (etc)...<br>
<br>
Imagine you had to choose from three people based upon what they say as an advisor for your community.<br>
<br>
Person Al says: &quot;I promise a chicken in my pot; a car in my garage.&quot;<br>
<br>
Person Bill says: &quot;I promise a chicken in every pot; a car in every garage.&quot;<br>
<br>
Person Cliff says: &quot;I promise that we will give more people chickens in their pot and more cars in their garages.&quot;<br>
<br>
Nobody will care about Al, he is clearly not thinking of anyone but himself. Nobody will believe Bill, he clearly doesn't have a clue. But Cliff will likely be listened to.<br>
<br>
On druids leaving the game - the past 6 months has seen a large group of people leaving for lots of reasons (DAoC) etc, etc. I am sure some have stated that the reason they left is because they were not having fun in the end game. This is also mentioned in the other classes too. An earlier post (sorry for not remembering who - but it was a great post) mentioned that we should examine our role in the end game and perhaps accept that it is different from our earlier role.<br>
<br>
Also, I know the moderators have their hands full with this topic. However, I have seen non-druids, druids, and moderators post what I would interpret as personal comments about the people instead of the arguements to the petition.<br>
<br>
Based upon the posts here, the one thing that druids want from this petition is more access to raids. They feel that the changes listed would help that. (Though I frankly doubt it.) As someone pointed out about 10 pages earlier, the end game is broken in one fundamental way - melee's stack, healers stack. Just about everyone else does not. This explains why we all focus on healing, since that one skill is something that might allow multiple druids to enter a raid and be desirable.<br>
<br>
However, the same limitation applies to all other priest classes. So along the lines of Cliff, why not propose something available to all priests, including druids. (I still like the idea of having a percentage heal 30% or 50% available to all priest classes as a rare drop level 60 spell.)<br>
<br>
And yes, increasing raid usefulness will increase your xp usefulness. Lets not be coy here and pretend that one does not relate to the other. It is much like Bill above, nobody believes it.<br>
<br>
By the way - I have seen some outstanding posts (on both sides). I have also noticed that Sobe is working overtime to read and record things. My complements. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uquiet.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Quiet</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_bluespot.gif" BORDER=0> at: 4/9/02 8:24:33 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ukryts44.showPublicProfile?language=EN>kryts44</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(4/9/02 11:47:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgroverants.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=650.topic&index=463>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://homepage.ntlworld.com/kryten.smeghead/kryts5.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Druid Petition</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Comparatively, for 200 mana a Shaman can heal 1,200 hitpoints in 24 seconds (30 seconds when you add the six-second cast time for Torpor). <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Topor is still a very rare spell and unatainable by your average level 60 shaman without paying ridiculous amounts for it.   If we're talking Raid only useage then Topor is not widely used for melle healing due to the side affects.   and seeing as its group only you would need a level 60 shaman in every group to make it effective.  Although at first glance the low mana cost makes it seem very powerfull, for raiding purposes its just another situational tool that can be added but in no way really makes us better healers.  Take topor away and we're all on chloroblast and for a shaman thats a very mana consuming way to heal on raids if your given a healing role.<br>
