 <p><a href="http://homepage.ntlworld.com/kryten.smeghead//"target="web"><img src="http://homepage.ntlworld.com/kryten.smeghead/sig.jpg" border="0"></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/bthedruidsgrove.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=faynedethe>Fayne Dethe</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/image/globalBlack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(4/9/02 11:52:19 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgroverants.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=650.topic&index=464>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Conversation: What about Us! (State of The Druid)</span><hr size=1>   People talk about the great number of druids, but fail to look at the number who are just port whores, powerlevelers, or 2nd boxed healer for someone's main character.  Just recently a good friend of mine quit her druid for her monk because she wasnt having any fun with the character either on raids or xp'ing (having to solo alot cause not wanted in xp groups).   Most druids in my guild have talked about quitting their druids for a twink, something is highly wrong with that.   Also, about grouping, where are all the groups that want druids?  I see them shouting out for clerics or shamans all the time in places like sebilis/VL.  Can sit at zones shouting LFG for hours and not get one, or go solo for inefficient xp with few places to go at high levels (I know people getting 1-2 pts AA xp daily in a couple of hrs while quadkiting will take ya like 2 days to get 1 pt unless u spend all day doing it). <p>Fayne Dethe<BR> 
Level 60 Druid of Xegony<BR>
Havenlight</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ufenrillikesdadead.showPublicProfile?language=EN>FenrilLikesDaDead</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(4/9/02 11:58:12 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgroverants.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=650.topic&index=465>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Conversation: What about Us! (State of The Druid)</span><hr size=1> Actually, Guild Magic is an excellent INDICATION of the population of the various classes.  I have it filtered to show only mains and no alts, but if you wish I can list those as well.<br>
Okay if druids are such a powerful class as you say they are, btw I have playing pen and paper RPGs for 20 yrs, then necros should be MORE powerful than druids.  Alas we're not.  In fact specialists in any field are more powerful than someone that's a generalist class.  Reason being is FOCUS.  At the cost of gaining that power is the being weaker in most other areas.  The cost of being generalized is that you can do many jobs well, but your not master of any of them.  That alone makes you very desirable, because if you lose a &lt;insert class here&gt; a druid can adequately fill in.  This makes you better than a specialist, because you CAN fill the role that is a specialization of another class.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uzephreckshadowreaver.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Zephreck Shadowreaver</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(4/9/02 11:59:06 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgroverants.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=650.topic&index=466>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Conversation: What about Us! (State of The Druid)</span><hr size=1> After reading this whole ridiculously long thread again the main thing that I see over and over again is the phrase &quot;effective in the end game&quot;. Well lets look at that a second.<br>
<br>
The &quot;end game&quot; aspect of this game was not designed by verant to be done solo. Every class has unique strengths and weaknesses. When my guild does a raid there are certain classes that must be there on all raids. Yes that is true. But it is not those classes that makes the raids successful. What makes end game raids truly work is good teamwork, co-operation, and good strategy. No one class makes or breaks a raid. All are needed. <br>
<br>
Never in all my time playing the game did my guild ever say &quot;druids don't attend our raids today&quot;. And lets face it if you are working on high end mobs in the end game you are doing it in a guild. EVERY class could use upgrades in areas. If you are wondering why so many other classes see this as whining it is because the tone of the arguments is &quot;Druids need this....&quot; It is written from the perspective of we druids (as individuals) need these things to feel more important / be more effective. If you are going to be persuasive and move an audience you may want to invest some effort into your target audience. Other druids are NOT your target audience. What person playing a druid would every say &quot;No please don't give me better heals, etc.&quot;  <br>
<br>
Your target audience should be other classes. Thus their views whether you appreciate them or not are important. Until other classes besides yourselves see your weakness as being something that needs to be addressed I highly doubt Verant will see it.<br>
<br>
There is a perception that Druids are a very powerful class.  While you may not see that *Most* people do. And that is why on average the most popular class picked is a druid. While you argue that your high end abilities need retooling you fail to address the fact that it is easy to get to the end game playing a druid. Yes soloing isn't as fun as grouping but at least you have the ability to. It is an option.<br>
<br>
My played time as a ranger is 149 days played. And I am level 57. I helped a friend (soloing not being pleveled) play a druid to level 50. It had less than 20 days played into it. <br>
<br>
Why? Due to the ability of the druid to kite. They are amazing classes. If every class looked at their weaknesses and didn't realize their potential then no one would stick with one class. <br>
<br>
This forum was made open to other classes. Keep that in mind. If you want to move verant you have to first move the other classes to see your points. Thus far I don't see you doing that effectively. Instead if anything you are alienating yourselves.<br>
<br>
As far as not being needed in groups there are many that cry that same plea. Ask a mage how frustrating it is only to be needed for COH. Ask a ranger how frustrating it is to be able to dish out damage but have the same durability once meleeing as a caster. Ask a warrior how frustrating it is to have a healer in order to do anything. Each class has a frustrating aspect to it. The key is not to whine and gripe about what you don't have but to use your mind to decide how best to use what you do have.<br>
<br>
That is what other classes do and that is what will make you truly wanted in end game encounters. Not some sort of ability, spell, etc. The endgame was made for people that rationally think and have patience and perserverance. <br>
<br>
Pulling ability, Complete heal chains, aggro transferrance, those are all skills that players hone as they learn and play the game and what makes or breaks the game. Not one specific spell or ability. Ever see someone play a monk that has never pulled before? Having Feign death does no good if you dont' know how to use it. What about a cleric that has never been part of a CH chain? Timing is all screwed up and MT dies and then you have wipeout. <br>
<br>
Being level 60 isn't just a number representing your abilities. What matters most is your ability to play that character. If your petition is to address your inability to do better in the end game perhaps you should also think about what druids can do with what they have already. Because for most druids that play the game that will be much more effective use of time than a wish list that most others who are not druids will ever agree to.<br>
<br>
/bow<br>
